To measure the sensitivity of G-CDs for Fe3+ determination, the PL spectra of G-CDs under different concentrations of Fe3+ ions were recorded. As shown in Fig. 7
                        a and b, the PL intensities at 520 nm decreased with the concentration of Fe3+. Additionally, a good linear correlation in the range of 20–1200 μM was observed, and the detection limit (LOD = 3σ/K, where σ represents the standard deviation, K denotes the slope of the standard curve) [40] was calculated to be 2.4 μM. With the addition of AA into the G-CDs-Fe3+ mixture, the fluorescence gradually recovered (Fig. 7c). As shown in Fig. 7d, (F–F0)/F0 is linearly correlated with the AA concentration (40–700 μM), and the LOD was measured to be 5 μM according to the equation of (F–F0)/F0 = 0.0041 [AA] – 0.25689 (R2 = 0.998). A comparison of detection results of AA was conducted among the reported literatures in terms of LOD and linear range (Table 1
                        ). Thus, the successive fluorescence change of G-CDs made it capable of being an “on-off-on” fluorescent sensor for simultaneous determination of Fe3+ and AA.
